{"parse":{"title":"Lawrence Paul","pageid":27446479,"revid":839461852,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">Not to be confused with <a href=\"/wiki/Lawrence_Paul_(Millbrook_First_Nation)\" title=\"Lawrence Paul (Millbrook First Nation)\">Lawrence Paul (Millbrook First Nation)</a>.</div>\n<p><b>Lawrence Paul</b> (June 29, 1925 \u2013 May 1, 2010) was a <a href=\"/wiki/Canada\" title=\"Canada\">Canadian</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Mi%27kmaq_people\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mi&#39;kmaq people\">Mi'kmaq</a> leader and <a href=\"/wiki/First_Nations\" title=\"First Nations\">First Nations</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Activist\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Activist\">activist</a>. Paul served as the chief of the <a href=\"/wiki/Membertou_First_Nation\" title=\"Membertou First Nation\">Membertou First Nation</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Nova_Scotia\" title=\"Nova Scotia\">Nova Scotia</a> from 1967 to 1969.<sup id=\"cite_ref-news_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-news-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Paul also co-founded the <a href=\"/wiki/Union_of_Nova_Scotia_Indians\" title=\"Union of Nova Scotia Indians\">Union of Nova Scotia Indians</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-news_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-news-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Paul was born on June 29, 1925, on Old Kings Road Reserve in <a href=\"/wiki/Sydney,_Nova_Scotia\" title=\"Sydney, Nova Scotia\">Sydney, Nova Scotia</a>.  Paul served in the <a href=\"/wiki/Canadian_military\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Canadian military\">Canadian military</a> during both <a href=\"/wiki/World_War_II\" title=\"World War II\">World War II</a> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Korean_War\" title=\"Korean War\">Korean War</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-news_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-news-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In 1967, Paul was elected for a two-year term as <a href=\"/wiki/Tribal_chief\" title=\"Tribal chief\">chief</a> of the <a href=\"/wiki/Membertou_First_Nation\" title=\"Membertou First Nation\">Membertou First Nation</a>, which is based in the <a href=\"/wiki/Cape_Breton_Regional_Municipality\" title=\"Cape Breton Regional Municipality\">Cape Breton Regional Municipality</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Nova_Scotia\" title=\"Nova Scotia\">Nova Scotia</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-news_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-news-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Most members of the Membertou First Nation lived without basic utilities, such as <a href=\"/wiki/Indoor_plumbing\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Indoor plumbing\">indoor plumbing</a>, during Paul's tenure as chief.<sup id=\"cite_ref-news_1-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-news-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> He worked to expose the Membertou's poor living conditions to the general public. Paul also cleared woodlands and upgrade facilities in and around the Membertou lands.<sup id=\"cite_ref-news_1-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-news-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>An <a href=\"/wiki/Advocate\" title=\"Advocate\">advocate</a> for First Nations, Paul co-founded an organization which became the <a href=\"/wiki/Union_of_Nova_Scotia_Indians\" title=\"Union of Nova Scotia Indians\">Union of Nova Scotia Indians</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-news_1-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-news-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> He also worked to alleviate <a href=\"/wiki/Alcoholism\" title=\"Alcoholism\">alcoholism</a> among First Nations communities.  He worked as a regional <a href=\"/wiki/Consultant\" title=\"Consultant\">consultant</a> on alcoholism prevention for the Canadian Department of National Health and Welfare.<sup id=\"cite_ref-news_1-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-news-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Paul also co-founded the Native Alcohol and Drug Abuse Counselling Association, and served as the association's <a href=\"/wiki/Executive_director\" title=\"Executive director\">executive director</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-news_1-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-news-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Additionally, he established a series of anti-alcoholism programs, with offices in <a href=\"/wiki/Prince_Edward_Island\" title=\"Prince Edward Island\">Prince Edward Island</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/New_Brunswick\" title=\"New Brunswick\">New Brunswick</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Boston,_Massachusetts\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Boston, Massachusetts\">Boston, Massachusetts</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-news_1-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-news-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The <a href=\"/wiki/Cape_Breton_University\" title=\"Cape Breton University\">University College of Cape Breton</a> awarded Paul an <a href=\"/wiki/Honorary_degree\" title=\"Honorary degree\">honorary degree</a> in 1996.<sup id=\"cite_ref-news_1-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-news-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Lawrence Paul died on May 1, 2010, at Cape Breton Regional Hospital in <a href=\"/wiki/Sydney,_Nova_Scotia\" title=\"Sydney, Nova Scotia\">Sydney, Nova Scotia</a>, at the age of 84.<sup id=\"cite_ref-news_1-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-news-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Lawrence_Paul&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-news-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-news_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-news_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-news_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-news_1-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-news_1-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-news_1-5\"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-news_1-6\"><sup><i><b>g</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-news_1-7\"><sup><i><b>h</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-news_1-8\"><sup><i><b>i</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-news_1-9\"><sup><i><b>j</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-news_1-10\"><sup><i><b>k</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-news_1-11\"><sup><i><b>l</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.ngnews.ca/Canada---World/News/2010-05-03/article-1050807/Lawrence-Paul,-Nova-Scotia-Mi%26rsquo%3Bkmaq-leader-and-pioneer,-dies-at-age-84/1\">\"Lawrence Paul, Nova Scotia Mi'kmaq leader and pioneer, dies at age 84\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_News_(New_Glasgow)\" title=\"The News (New Glasgow)\">The News (New Glasgow)</a></i>. 2010-05-03<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2010-05-22</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+News+%28New+Glasgow%29&amp;rft.atitle=Lawrence+Paul%2C+Nova+Scotia+Mi%E2%80%99kmaq+leader+and+pioneer%2C+dies+at+age+84&amp;rft.date=2010-05-03&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ngnews.ca%2FCanada---World%2FNews%2F2010-05-03%2Farticle-1050807%2FLawrence-Paul%2C-Nova-Scotia-Mi%2526rsquo%253Bkmaq-leader-and-pioneer%2C-dies-at-age-84%2F1&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALawrence+Paul\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Lawrence_Paul&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\